  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although the book \"Imagined Cosmopolis\" published by Peter Lang Verlag in 2019 has not yet garnered any citations or online mentions, its commercial presence on platforms like Amazon and Goodreads suggests a potential for reaching a broader audience interested in its themes.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Imagined Cosmopolis,\" published by Peter Lang Verlag in 2019, serves as a significant contribution to the discourse surrounding urban studies and cosmopolitanism. While the book currently has zero citations and no recorded community discussions across platforms such as Wikipedia, Reddit, and Bluesky, its availability on commercial platforms indicates a potential engagement with both academic and public readers.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's commercial linkage strength, rated at 0.9, is evidenced by its presence on major retail sites which could suggest an interest in its content from readers outside of academia. This commercial aspect may pave the way for broader discussions on its themes, even if formal academic uptake has yet to be established.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Additionally, the book's potential relevance to sustainability policies is noted with a strength value of 0.55, indicating that it contributes to conversations around global sustainability challenges. The presence of one Sustainable Development Goal within the context of the book further underscores its alignment with pressing global issues, even in the absence of direct citations or discussions.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, \"Imagined Cosmopolis\" presents itself as a foundational piece that may influence future discourse in its field. As discussions about urban environments and their cultural implications continue to evolve, this work could find its place in subsequent scholarly conversations, fostering connections between commercial and academic audiences alike.</p>",
